&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;"&gt;&lt;code class="language-zsh" data-lang="zsh"&gt;&lt;span style="display:flex;"&gt;&lt;span&gt;sudo pacman -S neovim
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Use the &lt;code&gt;.lua&lt;/code&gt; to conigure &lt;em&gt;NeoVim&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;can use the &lt;code&gt;.vim&lt;/code&gt; to configure &lt;em&gt;NeoVim&lt;/em&gt; too.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;h2 id="set-the-config-path-of-nvim"&gt;Set the config path of nvim&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In the linux system, the &lt;code&gt;nvim&lt;/code&gt; config directory local in the &lt;code&gt;~/.config/nvim&lt;/code&gt;. This PATH also called &lt;code&gt;runtime path&lt;/code&gt; , &lt;em&gt;NeoVim&lt;/em&gt; read the &lt;code&gt;~/.config/nvim/init.lua&lt;/code&gt; by default.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In theory, all the config things can be placed in this &lt;code&gt;.lua&lt;/code&gt;, but not a good idea.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>